Can you imagine Rock Around the Clock played on the “celestial” harps? Rave Harpers will transform your image of the angelic harp this June. Come join them as they perform a selection of fun pieces on the harp, which will include rock ‘n’ roll, jazz and even flamenco favourites. It will be a groovin’ evening!

About Rave Harpers

Rave Harpers is Singapore’s leading harp orchestra. Led and directed by Young Artist award winner Katryna Tan, this group was formed in 2004 and has since performed in various musical events and concerts. Members of the ensemble range from harp students as young as five years old to more advanced youth. In 2005, Rave Harpers successfully performed their first harp ensemble concert at the Esplanade Concert Hall with 17 harps. This was followed by a Christmas charity concert at the Arts House and various other appearances at National Library, Shaw Stage at the Singapore Botanical Gardens and Esplanade Recital Studio. Rave Harpers recorded their debut CD in 2008.

Rave Harpers was featured in Singapore Harp Festivals I, II and III, receiving rave reviews for their originality. Their repertoire includes a range of classical, Asian-themed pieces, swing, and contemporary music, many of which are arranged especially by director Katryna for the ensemble. Leading Singapore composer Dr Joyce Koh was also commissioned to write a piece When the Rain Speaks for the ensemble which was performed in HarpFest II 2008. New commissions have also been awarded to composers Eric Watson and Phang Kok Jun.

Rave Harpers’ overseas performance include Hong Kong, where they represented Singapore in the first Asian Harp Festival 2008; Malaysia in 2010; Ancenis, France in 2012, where they were invited to perform alongside other famous ensembles from around the world. The ensemble also had the privilege to be invited to perform the premiere concert at the Sentosa Resort World Concert Hall in conjunction with ChildAid 2009—the biggest Charity Concert event in Singapore for Children. They will perform the world premiere Eric Watson’s Golden Orb.

PLUCK – The Harp Musical was Rave Harpers’ biggest project yet in 2012 to celebrate the 10th anniversary of Rave Harps. Rave Harpers achieves another milestone in 2015 by performing as main cast in the second harp musical – PLUCK & the MAGIC BANYAN TREE.

As the group strength grows, the group has a new arm, a professional ensemble division Viva Rave whose members now leads the ensemble in its major activities.

The theme Strings Collide: East Bound sees VOX team up with Yuan Ting from local Chinese music ensemble QIN and zhong ruan musician Neil. They perform contemporary pieces, blending Chinese and western sounds using classical and traditional instruments.

VOX

VOX was formed five years ago to turn classical music on its head by reinterpreting pop/rock with classical instruments. With their bold interpretations of rock classics, such as Sweet Child of Mine and Paint It Black, as well as more recent hits by Adele, Muse, and Kings of Leon, VOX’s signature sound, fuelled by adrenaline, energy, and raw emotion, has turned heads at their live performances.

Neil Chua

Neil graduated from the prestigious Shanghai Conservatory of Music with a master’s degree in ruan (阮). In 2014, he was the first and only classical Chinese musician to be invited to participate in OneBeat, the U.S. Department of State’s Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs Exchange Programme, where he had the opportunity to interact, educate, and promote ruan (阮) to students and musicians from around the world.

Neil is committed to inspire people while promoting the rich culture of traditional Chinese music instrument. To this end, he dedicates his time to promoting the instrument ruan (阮) by working closely with composers and young musicians, and conducts regular classes to impart his skills to students.

Yuan Ting

An experienced performer with a wealth of teaching experience, Yuan Ting has been working with VOX on fusion music. Since their first collaboration as part of Esplanade’s Commune in 2015, she is now a frequent collaborator with VOX. Yuan Ting brings an oriental touch to VOX’s signature sound.

Curator: Lester Kong

A violinist by training, an experimenter at heart, Lester is a seasoned performer with a keen interest in music. He is currently a consultant of violin studies at Mandeville Conservatory of Music, an instrumental program instructor at Stamford America International School, and an instrumental consultant to National Institute of Education from 2014.

Lester is skilled at bringing out the best in musical fusions. Besides establishing himself as a rock violinist, he is best known as the frontman of VOX, Singapore’s first pop/rock string quartet.

Lester also does in-house arrangements and manages other bands under his company Vocalise Artistes Management. Since 2010, Lester has been appointed as the Music Director of the Victoria Junior College String Ensemble (VJCSE).

Swan Lake is famous for the 32 fouettés en tournant in Act 3. 

These fouettés are danced at the end of the "Black Swan" pas de deux by the ballerina playing Odile. The pas was an afterthought of Tchaikovsky's. It was not included in the original production. It consists of the opening adagio followed by a variation for the male dancer. This is followed by a variation for the ballerina. 

The whole concludes with a brisk movement for both dancers that includes the fouettés. Pierina Legnani first danced the fouettés in the Mariinsky production of 1895. Ballet-goers were uncertain about the 32 fouettés. Some thought they were just a stunt. Others found them exciting. These ballet-goers went to every performance to count the number of turns

Alvin Wong

Alvin is a graduate of Berklee College of Music with a degree in music performance. He is a part-time jazz guitar lecturer at Raffles Music College, and also teaches at international schools. He conducts several guitar ensembles of various primary and secondary schools and junior colleges.

Alvin performs with several groups, such as Felix Phang’s Imaginary forces, Dawn Wong's Ark Royale, and gypsy jazz group Gypsyfication.

Neil Chua

Neil graduated from the prestigious Shanghai Conservatory of Music with a master’s degree in ruan (阮). In 2014, he was the first and only classical Chinese musician to be invited to participate in OneBeat, the U.S. Department of State’s Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs Exchange Programme, where he had the opportunity to interact, educate, and promote ruan (阮) to students and musicians from around the world.

Neil is committed to inspire people while promoting the rich culture of traditional Chinese music instrument. A violinist by training, an experimenter at heart, Lester is a seasoned performer with a keen interest in music. He is currently a consultant of violin studies at Mandeville Conservatory of Music, an instrumental program instructor at Stamford America International School, and an instrumental consultant to National Institute of Education from 2014.

Lester is skilled at bringing out the best in musical fusions. Besides establishing himself as a rock violinist, he is best known as the frontman of VOX, Singapore’s first pop/rock string quartet.

Lester also does in-house arrangements and manages other bands under his company Vocalise Artistes Management. Since 2010, Lester has been appointed as the Music Director of the Victoria Junior College String Ensemble (VJCSE).

Taiko refers to a broad range of traditional Japanese drums with endless rhythmic possibilities.

KODO, Japan’s most celebrated taiko group, made its debut at the Berlin Festival in 1981. In Japanese, the word "kodo" has a double meaning: it can be translated as "heartbeat", which refers to the primal source of all rhythms; and can also mean “children of the drum", which in this context reflects the group’s desire to perform with the simple heart of a child. They tour extensively around the world and play a variety of taiko drums and other traditional instruments.

HIBIKIYA is a Japanese taiko drum and instrumental group in Singapore led by Namiko Sakai. What started out as a family activity grew to become a prominent ensemble that is constantly expanding and evolving. HIBIKIYA performs extensively in Singapore and also tours around Asia and the USA.

This collaboration between KODO and HIBIKIYA showcases the signature pieces of KODO. Adding to the high energy performance are the sounds of other traditional instruments such as the shinobue (Japanese flute) and shamisen (Japanese string instrument), as well as dance. Enjoy this exciting collaboration between Japan and Singapore as the two taiko groups meet on stage.

The ensemble uses the standard 13-stringed koto and the 17-stringed bass koto to play a variety of music ranging from traditional pieces to contemporary arrangements.
